commentText: This song is actually good. t's one of the few songs that I like and this may be because of this live action video. I like that this song, instead of focusing on the animatronic side of the horror, it focuses more on the human side of it. This aspect is not usually explored in FNAF songs and oh boy is it terrifying. One could argue that its scarier than the animatronics. It deals with ethics and morals that are constantly broken in reward for profit. It's sort of grimy and filthy in a way. I think that this is a very special addition to the FNAF song collection. All of the others are dark electronic songs while this one is upbeat, but even darker. Some of the visuals are actually quite disturbing. I adore this song. It might even be my favorite for its different take on the whole formula.

commentText: 1. Don't bad mouth anyone you've worked for (even if it's warranted) 2. Don't be desperate! Don't say "I'll do anything" tell them what you WANT to do for them. 3. Don't JUST answer the question, tell the story. Don't say what you did, say how you did it. 4. Don't say "I don't know how to do that" or "I've never seen that before" rather, say "let me think about that a moment" then connect to something similar. Don't be afraid to circle back to something... once or twice at most. 5. Don't ask them what their company does. You should know the company prior to the interview. Research them in advance. You can, however, ask for details about particular aspects of the company that interests you.

commentText: 1. In almost every interview I've had, I've "complained" about my previous company. Yes manning the job you just left lets the interviewer know you're lying straight through your teeth. You didn't leave the job because life was perfect.  The key is to do so tactfully, tell them exactly what convinced you to leave, or interview for their position over the job you have now. Maybe you weren't getting enough hours, "They didn't have enough work for me, so I'm looking for more." Maybe your boss was an absolute basketcase, "I didn't agree with management well enough to be productive in their environment."   All negative things about your last job can be spun in a neutral/positive way. The key is to not be negative.

commentText: I've only ever had a interview once in my life, it went horrible. I avoid any job that has a traditional interview system, the only reason they want an interview is to see how well you speak and communicate, and to test your confidence. But that basically means the introverts with amazing education & history will be more than likely pushed aside over an extrovert that did well in the interview.   Also the question: Tell me about yourself, needs to be abolished. Work is work, I don't want my employer knowing about my personal life. Everything they need, they already have on the CV that was sent to them.   I get that in certain job roles, the interview makes perfect sense, but say for an example a minimum wage job asking 'why do you want to work for our company over x' is such a dumb question that will always be answered with a lie.

Don't just say I don't know about it totally - Just connect some dots to that question with some of what you know. 5. Don't ask them what your company is doing - It shows your lack of preparation of job. Instead, ask about CSR Activities if they do.

commentText: Been in the Air Force for 17 years so far and I‚Äôve seen many memes, gifs, and videos poking fun at us. If you want to be a continuous student with a high level of personal responsibility, go aircrew or SERE Specialist. If you want to work with your hand and potentially work long hours, go aircraft maintenance, civil engineering, or logistics. commentText: All branches have their specific job, each having their own mission, Army is an occupying force with all the tools to take over and occupy an area or land. Now go see your local recruiter and have a nice day.

commentText: I Joined the Marines. Travelled the world, experienced so much awesome things and hardship. Flew on planes, sailed on ships packed like sardines, I loved, I lost, I laughed, I complained.   The Marines shaped me like a gem, polishing and cutting the edges until they got what they wanted. If a diamond cant handle the pressure it will break.   I lost and I gained. I respect all branches but there is a history from 1775, we had to memorize the battles in the past and famous warriors.   I would say to young men research as much as you can, don't get lied to for bonuses. And get your mos/ occupation in writing.   VA is paying for my college as we speak, but they cant give me back my hearing or marriage.   I thank God,  for being my battle buddy. Semper Fi. Do or die.

commentText: Public school teachers are being outsourced because most school districts require a master's degree and underpay their teachers. According to a study by the Economic Policy Institute, all across the country, teachers pay a financial penalty to serve the public mission of educating our kids instead of entering more lucrative professions. In my state that penalty is 16 cents to every dollar. When benchmarked with median household income, teachers in my state make the 9th lowest salary in the nation. Combined with the fact that we have the lowest teacher working conditions in the country, and that budgets are still being cut left and right, class sizes increasing, 30+ teaching positions being eliminated, it's no wonder that they're outsourcing these jobs to the lowest bidder. When the most important in-school factor in a child's education is the quality of teaching they receive, why would you put a larger focus on money than on the future of your country?

commentText: You nailed it on the culture piece! So many companies write generic job descriptions that sound exactly like their competitors, then wonder why they attract the wrong people. I've been working with companies on this exact problem, and here's what I've noticed: when you SHOW your culture instead of just describing it, everything changes. A 2-minute video of your actual team interacting, your real workspace, how decisions get made - that tells candidates more than any "we're like a family" job posting ever could.  The best part? People who don't fit your culture will self-select out before applying. You get fewer applications, but they're from people who actually WANT to work in your environment. It's like dating - you want someone who's excited about the real you, not some generic version you think they want to see. Have you experimented with video content to showcase culture authentically? The difference in candidate quality is pretty remarkable! üé•

Then you have to look over the ingredients, make sure you have them on hand and in the qty needed, make a list of what you don't have or need and go to the store and get it.  You also have to make sure you have the equipment.  Don't have a grater?  A juicer?  A masher?  Go get one or figure out a way using what you do have.  Then you need to organize everything.  Wet ingredients, dry ingredients what bowl sizes to hold what until you're ready to combine get the pots or cooker out.  Then you need to be able to measure.  Then you need to follow instructions.  There may be some element of timing involved. Marinate for a 8 hours or let soak for one hour, pre-heat the oven 15 minutes before placing roast to cook for one hour per lb.  So to be a GOOD cook, it requires certain skills.  Time management, organization, ability to follow an instructions.  So asking someone if they're a good cook or do they have a favorite recipe book or box of recipes, their answer can tell you a lot .

commentText: I'm laughing so hard at this man's posture as if he's some big time tech CEO lol I disagree with quite of bit of his perspective and the fact so many recruiters agree with him shows why there are so many bad companies to work for in this day and age. I don't find his mindset effective in the long-term at all.  A recruiter's life isn't easy when you "select the right person." Selecting is one thing, keeping them is a whole other skill set. Also, affecting culture shouldn't be a major priority of a company in hiring. People adapt to cultures if they value either the culture they're inserted in or what they're gaining from it, and the person's culture can contribute to making your company culture better and less myopic. A lot of great talent is wasted because companies learn to become obsessed about culture. Some people are perfectly happy just coming to work and being proud at doing their job well instead of having to fit in a culture. If you hire for culture, you hire personalities, not talent. More importantly, recruiters are terrible at putting themselves in the candidate's shoes and figuring out what the job will help fulfill in the life of that candidate. That's the most important piece if you want to keep them for a long time.

commentText: It's crazy how year after year we expect things to drastically change. As far as the US domestic league is concerned if you compare it to power houses yea we can't touch them. You have to realize not only how young this league is, but also how young the academies are. Realistically I don't think we've given it enough time to judge it fairly, but not only that if we look at the improvement of the MLS on a 5 year increment bases they've kept on growing in talent and popularity. I think it's important not to get impatient. In time, once we can produce good players in our academies we can look at pro/rel, but as of now that's not going to solve our problems mainly because we won't have as many people willing to invest in soccer. I mean how are the lower end teams going to stay alive if soccer isn't even that popular in our country. Once we can start producing great player then ok, maybe by then the interest will have increase to have enough fans to help support their local clubs. The problems always come down to money. commentText: They talk about Jurgen Klinsmann like he was a terrible coach. Under him the US was clearly the best team in the region, qualified for the world cup, got out of the group of death and beat more top ranked teams than any previous coach, while playing a more attacking form of soccer. It only went wrong due to the egos of the American players who stopped playing for him because he was calling them out. When Besler and Morris turned down moves to the EPL and Bundesliga to stay in the MLS, Jurgen called them out. You look now and Klinsmann was right because both players have stagnated in the MLS and wasted what potential they had. Jurgen wanted to change the US system for the better. He was the only person in US soccer that wanted to get rid of the pay to play system and said there wasn't enough working class White Black and Latino players in the US system. If you look at all the US soccer TV pundits they all have travel teams that earn them hundreds of thousands a year with the pay to play system and they were all against him because they were worried he was going to mess with their money and get rid of the pay to pay system.
